<text top="2417" left="1188" width="925" height="65" font="font2" id="p1_t98" reading_order_no="99" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">To  achieve  semantic  composition  that  includes  the </text>
<text top="2476" left="1139" width="974" height="57" font="font11" id="p1_t99" reading_order_no="100" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">context  of  the  exchanged  data  (Figure  2c),  context </text>
<text top="2521" left="1140" width="972" height="65" font="font2" id="p1_t100" reading_order_no="101" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">information  must  be  provided.  This  context  informa- </text>
<text top="2575" left="1140" width="973" height="65" font="font2" id="p1_t101" reading_order_no="102" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">tion  is  any  metadata  that  explicitly  describes  the </text>
<text top="2627" left="1140" width="972" height="65" font="font2" id="p1_t102" reading_order_no="103" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">meaning  of  the  data  to  be  exchanged  between  Web </text>
<text top="2680" left="1139" width="974" height="63" font="font0" id="p1_t103" reading_order_no="104" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">services.  When  Web  services’  inputs  and  outputs  are </text>
<text top="2731" left="1139" width="973" height="65" font="font2" id="p1_t104" reading_order_no="105" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">explicitly  described  using  metadata,  they  can  be  auto- </text>
